    summary:
      "Paul opens Romans not with small talk but with a thesis statement that will reshape Western civilization. He introduces himself as a doulos — a slave — of Jesus Christ. The word is blunt. He is not a consultant, not an advisor, not a thought leader. He belongs entirely to someone else. And then he lays out, in what reads like a compressed creed, who Jesus is: descended from David according to the flesh, declared Son of God in power by the resurrection. The entire Old Testament was pointing toward this moment, Paul says, and now the moment has arrived.\n\nWhat's striking about these opening verses is Paul's eagerness. He's writing to a church he didn't plant, in a city he's never visited, and he can barely contain himself. 'I am not ashamed of the gospel,' he says — which, given that the gospel centered on a man executed by Roman authority, was a provocative thing to say in a letter to Rome. The cross was Rome's favorite deterrent. Paul is telling Romans that their government's instrument of terror has become his instrument of hope.\n\nAnd then the thesis: 'The righteous shall live by faith.' Borrowed from Habakkuk, repurposed for a new era. This one sentence will ignite the Protestant Reformation fifteen centuries later, but for now it's just a Jewish tentmaker telling a mixed congregation in the capital of the world that everything they thought they knew about getting right with God is about to be turned upside down.",
