    summary:
      "Having announced the good news, Paul now explains why it's needed. And he starts not with individual sins but with a cosmic problem: humanity has suppressed the truth. God's existence, Paul argues, is self-evident from creation — 'clearly perceived' in the things that have been made — but people have chosen to look away. The result is not that God punishes them with wrath. The result is that God 'gives them over' to the consequences of their own choices. Three times Paul uses that devastating phrase: 'God gave them over.' This is not active punishment. It's divine withdrawal. God steps back and lets humanity experience the full weight of its own preferences.\n\nThe catalogue of sins that follows — sexual distortion, envy, murder, gossip, arrogance — is not a ranking from worst to best. Paul deliberately mixes what we'd consider 'major' sins with 'minor' ones. Gossip sits next to murder. Boasting sits next to ruthlessness. The point is not which sins are worst. The point is that the whole human project has gone sideways, top to bottom, and no one gets to stand on the sideline feeling superior.\n\nThis passage has been misused more than almost any in the New Testament — ripped from its rhetorical context and weaponized against specific groups. But Paul's audience didn't know where he was heading. He was building a trap. The religious reader who nods along thinking 'yes, those terrible sinners' is about to walk straight into chapter 2: 'Therefore you have no excuse, you who pass judgment.'",
