    summary:
      "Having dropped the bombshell that justification is by faith, Paul knows what his Jewish readers are thinking: 'What about Abraham? He's our father. He obeyed God. He was circumcised. He kept the covenant.' So Paul goes straight to the founder and makes a move that must have made every synagogue-trained reader gasp: Abraham was justified by faith before he was circumcised. The chronology matters. Genesis 15 — 'Abraham believed God, and it was credited to him as righteousness' — comes before Genesis 17, the covenant of circumcision. Faith first, circumcision second. Which means circumcision was a sign of a righteousness Abraham already had, not the cause of it.\n\nPaul is doing something radical with the Jewish origin story. He's not rejecting Abraham. He's reclaiming him. Abraham is not the father of the circumcised only — he's the father of all who believe, circumcised or not. The family tree just got a lot bigger.\n\nAnd then Paul zeroes in on the quality of Abraham's faith. It wasn't blind optimism. Abraham was nearly a hundred years old. Sarah's womb was 'as good as dead.' Everything in the observable world said this promise was impossible. And Abraham believed anyway — not because he was ignoring reality, but because he was trusting a God for whom reality includes resurrection. 'He considered his own body, which was as good as dead... and the barrenness of Sarah's womb. Yet he did not waver through unbelief.' That's not denial. That's a different calculation.",
