    verseEnd: 23,
    summary:
      "Paul anticipates the obvious objection to his grace-soaked theology: 'Should we go on sinning so that grace may increase?' His answer is as blunt as it gets: 'By no means!' And then he explains why, using the imagery of baptism. When you were baptized, Paul says, you were buried with Christ. You went under. The old you — the one enslaved to sin — died. And the person who came up out of the water is someone new, 'alive to God in Christ Jesus.'\n\nThis is not metaphorical fluff. Paul is describing a real change in identity. The language is stark: you were slaves of sin, and now you are slaves of righteousness. You switched owners. You don't serve the old master anymore. And Paul knows this is an uncomfortable metaphor — he even says, 'I am speaking in human terms because of your natural limitations' — but he uses it anyway because it captures something essential: freedom in the Christian sense is not the absence of all obligation. It's serving the right master.\n\nThe chapter closes with one of the most quotable lines in the letter: 'The wages of sin is death, but the free gift of God is eternal life in Christ Jesus our Lord.' Wages versus gift. Earned versus given. The asymmetry is the whole point. Death is what you get paid. Life is what you're given.",
    significance:
      "Romans 6 is the hinge between Paul's doctrine of justification and his teaching on sanctification. Justification changes your legal standing; sanctification changes your actual life. Paul's point is that the two cannot be separated. If grace is real, it doesn't produce more sin — it produces a new kind of life. Baptism is the enacted symbol of this: death and resurrection compressed into a liturgical moment.\n\nThe 'slavery' metaphor is also crucial for understanding Paul's view of human freedom. For Paul, nobody is truly free. You're either enslaved to sin (which leads to death) or enslaved to righteousness (which leads to life). The question is not whether you serve. It's whom.",
    relationalNote:
      "Paul is writing to a community that includes both former slaves and slave owners. The metaphor of slavery was not abstract for them — it was their daily reality. When Paul says, 'You have been set free from sin and have become slaves of righteousness,' he's using language that would have landed differently depending on your social position. For actual slaves in the congregation, the idea of belonging to a good master who leads to life rather than death would have been both familiar and revolutionary.",
    conceptualNote:
      "The theology of baptism in Romans 6 is participationist: believers don't just hear about Christ's death and resurrection — they participate in it. 'We have been united with him in a death like his.' This is not spectating. It's dying. The baptismal waters are, symbolically, a grave. And the coming-up is a resurrection. Paul is saying that the Christian life begins with a funeral — your own — and that everything after is lived from the other side of death.",
    climateNote:
      "In the Roman world, manumission (freeing a slave) often involved a symbolic transaction at a temple, where a god 'purchased' the slave's freedom. Paul may be echoing this practice: believers have been 'purchased' from sin's ownership and now belong to God. The Roman Christians would have understood this as a change of legal status with real-world consequences — not just a spiritual abstraction but a new social identity.",
    modernParallel:
      "The question 'Should we keep sinning so grace can increase?' is still asked, usually in less obvious forms. When a teenager says, 'Why bother being good if God forgives everything anyway?' — that's Romans 6:1. When a church tolerates corruption because 'we're all sinners saved by grace' — that's Romans 6:1. Paul's answer is not legalism (try harder) or permissiveness (it doesn't matter). His answer is identity: you're a different person now. Dead people don't keep doing what they used to do.\n\nThe slavery metaphor makes modern readers uncomfortable, as it should. But Paul's point is not that slavery is good. His point is that everyone serves something. You serve your career, your reputation, your appetites, your ideology, your comfort — or you serve God. The myth of total autonomy is exactly that: a myth. The real question is which master leads to life and which leads to death.\n\nAnd 'wages of sin is death' — wages. Not punishment. Not sentence. Wages. It's what you earned. You worked for it. You showed up every day and put in the hours. Death is the paycheck. But life? Life is the gift. Nobody works for a gift. That's what makes it a gift.",
